article.description: Zam Fredrick scored a career-high 22 points as Georgia Tech upset North Carolina State 71-68 Sunday to end an eight-game losing streak, its longest in 25 years.
article.headline: NC State dealt damaging ACC loss
article.linkText: Georgia Tech upsets NC State, halts eight-game slide
article.story: ATLANTA (AP) -- Reserve Zam Fredrick wants his starting job back. Fredrick scored a career-high 22 points as Georgia Tech upset North Carolina State (No. 15 ESPN/USA Today, No. 16 AP) 71-68 Sunday to end an eight-game losing streak, its longest in 25 years. Frederick's 3-pointer with 3:22 left gave Tech a 67-62 lead. He hit a short jumper before the shot clock expired to push the lead to 71-65 with 1:03 left. A 3-pointer by the Wolfpack's Cameron Bennerman with 50 seconds left cut the lead to three points. The Wolfpack had a chance to tie in the final seconds. After Bennerman missed a 3-point try, the clock expired with Gavin Grant looking for a teammate beyond the 3-point line. Fredrick had started 18 games this season. Since losing his starting job, he's set personal scoring highs in two straight games. The sophomore guard had 19 points in Tech's loss at Florida State Thursday night. "I think a lot of pressure is off him coming off the bench," said Ra'Sean Dickey, who added 14 points for Tech. Fredrick said he may be more relaxed after watching the game from the bench for a few minutes before entering the game. "Sometimes when we get off to a slow start I feel that's my fault," Fredrick said. Tech coach Paul Hewitt is not likely to change Fredrick's role making 16-of-23 shots the last two games. Fredrick made 9-of-12 shots on Sunday. "Maybe the reduced minutes has made him a little fresher and given him a little more energy because he definitely had some bursts where he was blowing by his man," Hewitt said. "I think it's a combination of him being a little fresher and taking quality shots." North Carolina State coach Herb Sendek didn't like how the game ended. Grant got the rebound off Bennerman's miss, but couldn't find an open man beyond the arc when the buzzer sounded. "It wasn't a designed play," Sendek said. "Cameron has obviously made those kinds of shots for us before and that one just didn't go down." Ilian Evtimov led North Carolina State (19-5 overall, 8-3 Atlantic Coast Conference) with 17 points and nine rebounds. Engin Atsur added 15 and Bennerman had 13. Tech (10-12 overall, 3-8 ACC) won for the first time since a Jan. 10 victory over Centenary. Their losing streak began with an 87-78 loss at North Carolina State on Jan. 11. Fredrick had 11 points in that game, making only 4 of 13 shots. "He had 11 points the first time we played, but he really made tough plays, big shots and showed how talented he was," Sendek said "Today he really got going and was in a zone and certainly was a major factor in their victory." Fredrick scored 11 points by halftime, and added six assists with only one turnover. Tech ended a seven-game losing streak in the series with the Wolfpack, who had their four-game winning streak snapped. "When you've lost eight in a row, there's definitely a sense of relief," Hewitt said. "We've got to try to keep getting better." Three of Tech's last four losses came by a combined total of four points. "I've under-coached them," said Hewitt, who took Tech to the national championship game two years ago. "I haven't overrated them." Tech, which has lost four ACC games after leading at halftime, made good on a lead at the break this time. Tech made 5 of 6 3-point shots, including two by Fredrick, to lead 35-29 at halftime. North Carolina State center Cedric Simmons fouled out with five points with 3:55 left, seven below his average. The Wolfpack made four 3-pointers in the first 5 minutes of the second half, and a 3 by Bethel at the 15:10 mark gave the visitors at 45-44 lead, their last of the game. Tech answered quickly with a 3-pointer by Anthony Morrow, who had 11 points.
